<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>SINGLE REDUCTION, TANDEM AXLE: INTERNATIONAL - ASSEMBLE - PINION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="4">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1400939">Figure 39</hotlnk>
        </para>
        <figure id="f1400939" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1400939" filename="../figg14/g1400939.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 39. Forward Rear Axle and Rear Rear Axle Components</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. CARRIER CASE</callout1>
                <callout1>2. PINION PILOT BEARING</callout1>
                <callout1>3. DRIVE PINION</callout1>
                <callout1>4. BEARING CONE</callout1>
                <callout1>5. BEARING CUP</callout1>
                <callout1>6. POSITION SHIMS (SELECTIVE)</callout1>
                <callout1>7. PINION BEARING CAGE</callout1>
                <callout1>8. PRELOAD SPACER (SELECTIVE)</callout1>
                <callout1>9. BEARING CUP</callout1>
                <callout1>10. BEARING CONE</callout1>
                <callout1>11. DRIVEN GEAR</callout1>
                <callout1>12. PINION NUT SPACER</callout1>
                <callout1>13. ROLL PIN</callout1>
                <callout1>14. CASTELLATED PINION NUT</callout1>
                <callout1>15. BOLT</callout1>
                <callout1>16. BOLT</callout1>
                <callout1>17. PINION NUT</callout1>
                <callout1>18. END YOKE</callout1>
                <callout1>19. PINION SEAL</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press inner pinion bearing cone onto the pinion gear.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press roller bearing onto the pinion gear.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Bearing must be installed with radius in bore toward pinion gear.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Stake roller bearing in nine places (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400940">Figure 40</hotlnk>), using a staking tool. Refer to
                <hotlnk document="s14009_43.xml" xrefid="hl1400901">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400940" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400940" filename="../figg14/g1400940.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 40. Stake Roller Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Make sure all cage bores are free of nicks, dirt, or any contamination.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install inner pinion bearing cup into pinion cage.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cup into pinion cage.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge or shim stock .0015 inch (.0381 mm) to ensure bearing cups are completely
                seated in bearing bores (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400941">Figure 41</hotlnk>). This is necessary for proper pinion position.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400941" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400941" filename="../figg14/g1400941.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 41. Use Feeler Gauge</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place selective preload spacer that was removed during disassembly onto pinion.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place pinion cage onto pinion gear inner bearing.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cone onto pinion.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect rear carrier end yoke seal surface for grooves caused by lip of seal. If grooves can
                be detected with fingernail, it should be replaced.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install gear onto pinion of forward carrier. Torque castellated nut to 600 ft-lbs. (813 N&#8226;m).
                If hole in pinion does not align with slots in nut, tighten nut until they are aligned. Do not install
                roll pin at this time.
            </para>
            <para>On rear carriers, install end yoke (use service tool ZTSE 4336) onto pinion without seal to allow
                proper setting of bearing preload. Tighten pinion nut to 900 to 1200 ft-lbs. (1220 to 1627 N&#8226;m).
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Pinion cage should be rotated while tightening pinion nut to seat and align the pinion
                        bearings.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>There are two methods of measuring pinion bearing preload and both are acceptable. Mechanic's
                preference and available tools determine which method will be used.
            </para>
            <para>The first method uses a spring pull scale and a strong cord approximately 8 ft. long.</para>
            <para>The second method uses a torque wrench.</para>
            <para>Both methods measure torque to rotate.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To measure preload with the spring scale, clamp the end yoke horizontally in a soft-jawed
                vise. Attach one end of cord to a bolt hole in the pinion cage, wrap cord around pinion cage and attach
                the other end of cord to the spring scale (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1400942">Figure 42</hotlnk>). Rotate pinion cage by pulling scale. Read scale during
                fourth revolution. Scale reading must be between 3 and 9 lbs.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1400942" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1400942" filename="../figg14/g1400942.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 42. Attach Spring Scale</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To measure preload with a torque wrench, assemble pinion cage into the carrier and install
                two mounting bolts to anchor the unit. Rotate pinion gear with a torque wrench. Torque measurement will
                be taken during fourth revolution and must be between 10 and 40 in-lbs. (1.1 and 4.5 N&#8226;m) without
                pinion seal (rear).
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When preload reading does not fall within allowable limits, bearing load can be increased by
                        using a thinner spacer or decreased by using a thicker spacer.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>.001" (.025 mm) change in preload spacer thickness changes scale reading by approximately 10
                        lbs. .001" change in preload spacer will change torque to rotate by approximately 30 in-lbs.
                        (3.4 N&#8226;m). (This is only a guide. Individual carriers may vary slightly.)
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>The pinion bearing spacers are available in the following thicknesses. Measure the spacer before
                assembly to assure correct thickness.
            </para>
        </step1>
